  "prompt": "Can myopia be cured?",
  "response": "As of now, myopia, also known as nearsightedness, cannot be \"cured\" in the traditional sense. However, there are several effective ways to manage and correct the condition:\n\n1. **Eyeglasses and Contact Lenses**: These are the most common methods used to correct myopia. They help focus light correctly on the retina, improving vision.\n\n2. **Orthokeratology (Ortho-K)**: This non-surgical procedure involves wearing specially designed rigid gas-permeable contact lenses overnight to temporarily reshape the cornea.\n\n3. **Refractive Surgery**: Procedures such as LASIK or PRK can permanently change the shape of the cornea to reduce or eliminate the need for glasses or contact lenses.\n\n4. **Pharmacological Treatments**: Atropine eye drops, particularly in low doses, have shown promise in slowing the progression of myopia in children.\n\n5. **Lifestyle and Environmental Adjustments**: Increasing time spent outdoors and reducing time on near work or screens can help slow the progression of myopia in children.\n\nResearch into more permanent solutions is ongoing and future advancements may provide more options for those with myopia. It's important to consult with an eye care professional to determine the best approach for managing the condition.",
